ladders.explanation:
The brute force approach solves the maximal square problem by systematically examining every possible square in the binary matrix. The intuition is straightforward: for each cell that could be the top-left corner of a square, we try expanding the square size until we either hit the matrix boundaries or find a '0' that breaks the all-ones condition. This exhaustive search guarantees we find the maximum square, though it's computationally expensive.

Algorithm: 1) Initialize max_side = 0. 2) For each cell (i,j) in the matrix: a) If matrix[i][j] == '1', set current_max = 1 and update max_side. b) For k from 1 to min(m-i, n-j)-1: i) Check if all cells in the square from (i,j) to (i+k,j+k) are '1' by scanning rows i to i+k and columns j to j+k. ii) If all are '1', update current_max = k+1 and max_side. iii) If any '0' found, break. 3) Return max_side².

Time complexity: O(m*n*min(m,n)²) because for each of m*n cells, we check up to min(m,n) square sizes, each requiring O(k²) checks. Space: O(1).

Connection to L1: This uses the square validation subroutine from L1 repeatedly for different positions and sizes.

Common mistakes: 1) Forgetting to check the initial cell (size 1 square). 2) Incorrect boundary conditions causing index errors. 3) Not breaking early when a '0' is found. 4) Returning side length instead of area.

Real code pattern:
def maximalSquare(matrix):
    if not matrix: return 0
    m, n = len(matrix), len(matrix[0])
    max_side = 0
    for i in range(m):
        for j in range(n):
            if matrix[i][j] == '1':
                max_side = max(max_side, 1)
                current_max = 1
                bound = min(m-i, n-j)
                for k in range(1, bound):
                    valid = True
                    for x in range(i, i+k+1):
                        for y in range(j, j+k+1):
                            if matrix[x][y] == '0':
                                valid = False
                                break
                        if not valid: break
                    if valid:
                        current_max = k+1
                        max_side = max(max_side, current_max)
                    else:
                        break
    return max_side * max_side

This subroutine is the heart of the brute force approach. Given a starting position (top-left corner) and a side length, it verifies whether every cell in that square region contains the value '1'. The intuition is simple: a square is valid only if all its constituent cells meet the condition. This check must be exhaustive because a single '0' anywhere in the square invalidates it.

Algorithm: 1) Input: matrix, start row i, start column j, side length k. 2) For row from i to i+k-1: a) For column from j to j+k-1: i) If matrix[row][col] == '0', return False. 3) Return True.

Time complexity: O(k²) where k is the side length, since we check k² cells. Space: O(1).

Connection to L0: L0 calls this subroutine for each potential square size at each starting position to determine validity.

Common mistakes: 1) Off-by-one errors in loop boundaries. 2) Not handling edge cases where square extends beyond matrix boundaries (should be handled by caller). 3) Returning early without checking all cells.

